{
  "How many cells does meiosis produce from one parent cell, and are they genetically identical?": "",
  "Two genetically different diploid cells": "",
  "Four genetically unique haploid cells (gametes)": "",
  "Two genetically identical diploid cells": "",
  "Four genetically identical haploid cells": "",
  "Meiosis consists of two consecutive divisions (meiosis I and meiosis II) that start with one diploid cell (2n) and produce four haploid cells (n). Each of the four resulting gametes is genetically unique because crossing over during prophase I and independent assortment during metaphase I shuffle alleles into new combinations.": "",
  "How does meiosis change the chromosome number of a cell?": "",
  "It doubles the chromosome number from haploid to diploid": "",
  "It reduces the number to one-quarter of the original": "",
  "It reduces the chromosome number from diploid (2n) to haploid (n)": "",
  "It keeps the chromosome number the same": "",
  "Meiosis is called a reduction division because it halves the chromosome number. In humans, a diploid cell (2n = 46) produces haploid gametes (n = 23). This reduction is essential for sexual reproduction — when two haploid gametes fuse at fertilization, the diploid number is restored in the zygote.": "",
  "What are the two main divisions of meiosis, and what does each accomplish?": "",
  "Both divisions separate sister chromatids": "",
  "Both divisions separate homologous chromosomes": "",
  "Meiosis I separates sister chromatids; Meiosis II separates homologs": "",
  "Meiosis I separates homologous chromosomes (reduction division); Meiosis II separates sister chromatids (equational division)": "",
  "Meiosis I is the reduction division — homologous chromosome pairs are separated, cutting the chromosome number in half (diploid to haploid). Meiosis II is the equational division — similar to mitosis, it separates sister chromatids. The result after both divisions is four haploid cells from one diploid cell.": "",
  "When and where does crossing over occur during meiosis?": "",
  "During metaphase II when chromosomes line up": "",
  "During prophase I, when homologous chromosomes pair (synapse) and exchange DNA segments at chiasmata": "",
  "During S phase when DNA replicates": "",
  "During anaphase I when homologs separate": "",
  "Crossing over occurs specifically during prophase I of meiosis. Homologous chromosomes pair up side by side (synapsis) to form tetrads. Non-sister chromatids of the homologous pair then exchange corresponding DNA segments at points called chiasmata. This recombination creates new allele combinations on each chromatid, greatly increasing genetic diversity.": "",
  "What is independent assortment, and how does it create genetic variation?": "",
  "All maternal chromosomes go to one pole and paternal to the other, creating two types of gametes only": "",
  "Genes on the same chromosome are always inherited together regardless of recombination frequency": "",
  "Homologous pair orientation is random at metaphase I, so each gamete gets a different mix of maternal and paternal chromosomes — in humans, 2²³ ≈ 8.4 million possible combinations": "",
  "Sister chromatids separate randomly during meiosis II, generating new combinations of alleles": "",
  "Independent assortment occurs during metaphase I when homologous chromosome pairs line up at the metaphase plate. The orientation of each pair is random — the maternal homolog can face either pole independently of every other pair. With 23 pairs in humans, this produces 2²³ (about 8.4 million) possible gamete combinations. Combined with crossing over, the genetic diversity is essentially limitless.": "",
  "What are homologous chromosomes?": "",
  "Chromosomes that have been broken and repaired by crossing over": "",
  "Two identical copies of the same chromosome joined at the centromere (sister chromatids)": "",
  "Chromosomes found only in reproductive cells": "",
  "A matching pair of chromosomes — one from each parent — that carry the same genes at the same loci but may have different alleles": "",
  "Homologous chromosomes (homologs) are a pair of chromosomes — one inherited from the mother and one from the father — that are similar in size and shape and carry genes for the same traits at corresponding positions (loci). While they carry the same genes, they may have different versions (alleles) of those genes. Humans have 23 pairs of homologs (22 autosomal pairs + 1 sex chromosome pair).": "",
  "How many chromosomes do human gametes (sperm and egg cells) contain?": "",
  "23 chromosomes (haploid) — one from each homologous pair": "",
  "12 chromosomes, which is one-quarter of the diploid number found in somatic body cells": "",
  "92 chromosomes, representing the tetraploid number produced by DNA replication before division": "",
  "46 chromosomes (diploid), the same number found in somatic body cells before any cell division": "",
  "Human gametes are haploid (n = 23), meaning they contain one chromosome from each of the 23 homologous pairs (22 autosomes + 1 sex chromosome). When a sperm (23) and egg (23) fuse during fertilization, the resulting zygote has the full diploid complement of 46 chromosomes (2n = 46).": "",
  "What happens during fertilization to restore the chromosome number?": "",
  "Chromosomes are duplicated within the egg before division": "",
  "A diploid cell undergoes another round of meiosis": "",
  "Two diploid cells merge their chromosomes": "",
  "A haploid sperm (n = 23) fuses with a haploid egg (n = 23) to form a diploid zygote (2n = 46)": "",
  "Fertilization (syngamy) is the fusion of two haploid gametes to produce a diploid zygote. The sperm contributes 23 chromosomes (22 autosomes + X or Y) and the egg contributes 23 chromosomes (22 autosomes + X). The resulting zygote inherits 46 chromosomes in 23 pairs, restoring the diploid number for all subsequent mitotic divisions.": "",
  "What is nondisjunction, and what can it cause?": "",
  "Normal separation of chromosomes during cell division": "",
  "The exchange of DNA between homologous chromosomes": "",
  "The normal pairing of chromosomes during synapsis": "",
  "The failure of chromosomes to separate properly during meiosis, producing gametes with abnormal chromosome numbers (aneuploidy)": "",
  "Nondisjunction is the failure of homologous chromosomes (in meiosis I) or sister chromatids (in meiosis II) to separate properly. This produces gametes with one extra chromosome (n + 1) or one missing chromosome (n − 1). If these gametes are fertilized, the resulting offspring has aneuploidy (abnormal chromosome count) — such as trisomy 21 (Down syndrome, 47 chromosomes) or monosomy X (Turner syndrome, 45 chromosomes).": "",
  "How does spermatogenesis differ from oogenesis in the number of functional gametes produced?": "",
  "Both produce 2 functional gametes": "",
  "Both produce four equally-sized functional gametes": "",
  "Spermatogenesis produces 4 functional sperm; oogenesis produces only 1 functional egg plus 2-3 small polar bodies": "",
  "Spermatogenesis produces 1 sperm; oogenesis produces 4 eggs": "",
  "In spermatogenesis, cytoplasm divides equally at each meiotic division, producing four same-sized functional sperm. In oogenesis, the cytoplasm divides unequally — one large cell retains most cytoplasm, nutrients, and organelles (the future egg) while the small polar bodies receive minimal cytoplasm and degenerate. This asymmetric division maximizes the egg's resource stockpile for early embryonic development.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes meiosis?": "",
  "Cell division that produces two identical diploid daughter cells for growth and repair": "",
  "Programmed cell death triggered by DNA damage": "",
  "The process by which a cell copies its DNA before division": "",
  "A two-stage cell division (meiosis I and II) that produces four genetically unique haploid gametes from one diploid cell": "",
  "Meiosis is a specialized form of cell division that occurs only in reproductive organs (gonads). Starting from one diploid cell (2n), it produces four haploid cells (n) through two sequential divisions. Meiosis I separates homologous chromosomes (the reduction division) and meiosis II separates sister chromatids. The key distinction from mitosis is that meiosis halves the chromosome number and produces genetically unique cells through crossing over and independent assortment.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes crossing over?": "",
  "The random orientation of chromosome pairs at the metaphase plate": "",
  "The exchange of DNA segments between non-sister chromatids of homologous chromosomes during prophase I, creating new allele combinations": "",
  "The separation of homologous chromosomes during anaphase I": "",
  "The duplication of chromosomes during S phase of interphase": "",
  "Crossing over (genetic recombination) occurs during prophase I when homologous chromosomes are synapsed together as tetrads. Non-sister chromatids from each homolog physically break and rejoin at corresponding positions, swapping DNA segments. The visible points of exchange are called chiasmata. This process shuffles alleles between maternal and paternal chromosomes, producing recombinant chromatids with unique allele combinations not present in either parent.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes independent assortment?": "",
  "The controlled destruction of faulty chromosomes": "",
  "The random, independent orientation of each homologous chromosome pair at the metaphase I plate, producing diverse gamete chromosome combinations": "",
  "The exchange of genetic material between chromatids during prophase I": "",
  "The ordered separation of sister chromatids during mitosis": "",
  "Independent assortment (Mendel's Second Law) means that during metaphase I, the orientation of each homologous pair at the metaphase plate is random and independent of all other pairs. For example, whether chromosome 1's maternal copy faces the top pole has no influence on which way chromosome 2's maternal copy faces. In humans, this generates 2²³ (about 8.4 million) possible chromosome combinations per gamete — without even counting crossing over.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes haploid (n)?": "",
  "A cell containing two complete sets of chromosomes — one maternal set and one paternal set": "",
  "A cell with three sets of chromosomes (triploid)": "",
  "A cell that has lost all chromosomes during division": "",
  "A cell containing only one set of chromosomes (half the diploid number) — such as human gametes with 23 chromosomes": "",
  "Haploid (written as 'n') describes a cell with a single set of chromosomes — one member from each homologous pair. In humans, the haploid number is 23 (n = 23). Gametes (sperm and egg) are haploid cells produced by meiosis. The haploid state is essential for sexual reproduction: when two haploid gametes fuse at fertilization, they restore the diploid number (2n = 46) in the zygote.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes diploid (2n)?": "",
  "A cell containing one set of chromosomes, like a gamete": "",
  "A cell containing two complete sets of chromosomes (one from each parent) — such as human somatic cells with 46 chromosomes (23 pairs)": "",
  "A cell with four sets of chromosomes (tetraploid)": "",
  "A cell that has undergone meiosis and lost half its chromosomes": "",
  "Diploid (written as '2n') describes a cell with two complete sets of chromosomes — one set inherited from each parent. These chromosomes exist as homologous pairs. In humans, the diploid number is 46 (2n = 46), consisting of 22 pairs of autosomes and 1 pair of sex chromosomes. All somatic (body) cells are diploid. The diploid state ensures each gene has two copies (alleles), which is important for genetic diversity and masking harmful recessive mutations.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes nondisjunction?": "",
  "The normal separation of chromosomes during anaphase": "",
  "The exchange of DNA between non-sister chromatids": "",
  "The pairing of homologous chromosomes during synapsis": "",
  "The failure of chromosomes to separate properly during meiosis (or mitosis), producing cells with abnormal chromosome numbers (aneuploidy)": "",
  "Nondisjunction is a division error where chromosomes fail to separate properly. It can occur in meiosis I (homologs fail to separate) or meiosis II (sister chromatids fail to separate). The result is gametes with an extra chromosome (n + 1) or a missing chromosome (n − 1). If these abnormal gametes participate in fertilization, the offspring has aneuploidy — for example, trisomy 21 (Down syndrome, 3 copies of chromosome 21) or monosomy X (Turner syndrome, only one X chromosome).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a gamete?": "",
  "A diploid cell that undergoes growth and repair": "",
  "A haploid reproductive cell (sperm or egg) produced by meiosis that fuses with another gamete during fertilization to form a diploid zygote": "",
  "Any cell in the body that can divide by mitosis": "",
  "A cell that has been damaged by nondisjunction": "",
  "A gamete is a specialized haploid (n) reproductive cell produced by meiosis in the gonads. In animals, male gametes are sperm (produced in the testes via spermatogenesis) and female gametes are eggs/ova (produced in the ovaries via oogenesis). Gametes are the only cells in the body that are haploid — all other cells (somatic cells) are diploid. The fusion of two gametes during fertilization restores the diploid state.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes synapsis?": "",
  "The random alignment of chromosomes at the metaphase plate": "",
  "The precise pairing of homologous chromosomes side by side during prophase I, held together by the synaptonemal complex, enabling crossing over": "",
  "The separation of sister chromatids during anaphase II": "",
  "The formation of the cleavage furrow during cytokinesis": "",
  "Synapsis is the process during prophase I where homologous chromosomes find each other and pair up intimately along their length. A protein structure called the synaptonemal complex (SC) zips the homologs together like a molecular zipper. This tight pairing is essential for crossing over — it aligns corresponding gene loci so that DNA exchange occurs between the correct regions of non-sister chromatids.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a tetrad (bivalent)?": "",
  "Four separate chromosomes that line up together at metaphase": "",
  "A single chromosome composed of two sister chromatids": "",
  "A group of four chromatids formed when a pair of homologous chromosomes (each consisting of two sister chromatids) synapse during prophase I": "",
  "The four haploid cells produced at the end of meiosis": "",
  "A tetrad (also called a bivalent) is the structure formed during prophase I when two homologous chromosomes synapse. Since each homolog has been replicated and consists of two sister chromatids, the paired structure contains four chromatids total (hence 'tetrad'). The bivalent is also called a tetrad because of these four chromatids. Crossing over occurs within tetrads, with non-sister chromatids exchanging DNA segments at chiasmata.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes genetic variation?": "",
  "Differences in DNA sequences and allele combinations among individuals in a population, generated by crossing over, independent assortment, and random fertilization": "",
  "The process of DNA replication during S phase that ensures genetic continuity between parent and daughter cells": "",
  "The failure of chromosomes to separate during meiosis, resulting in aneuploidy in the daughter cells produced": "",
  "All organisms in a population having identical DNA sequences, which is common in asexually reproducing species": "",
  "Genetic variation refers to the diversity of allele combinations in a population. Meiosis generates variation through three mechanisms: (1) crossing over shuffles alleles between homologs, (2) independent assortment randomly combines maternal and paternal chromosomes in gametes (2²³ ≈ 8.4 million combinations in humans), and (3) random fertilization pairs any sperm with any egg. This variation is the raw material for natural selection and is essential for the long-term survival and adaptation of species.": "",
  "A lily plant (2n = 24) produces pollen grains through meiosis. A genetics student wants to know how many chromosomes each pollen grain nucleus contains and whether the maternal and paternal chromosomes are mixed. What should she conclude?": "",
  "Each pollen grain has 12 chromosomes (haploid), containing a random mix of maternal and paternal chromosomes due to independent assortment and crossing over": "",
  "Each pollen grain has 24 chromosomes, but they are identical to the parent": "",
  "Each pollen grain has 6 chromosomes because meiosis divides by four": "",
  "Each pollen grain has 24 chromosomes, all from the mother plant": "",
  "Meiosis halves the chromosome number, so a lily cell with 2n = 24 produces gametes (pollen) with n = 12 chromosomes. During meiosis I, independent assortment shuffles maternal and paternal chromosomes randomly — each pollen grain receives a unique combination of 12 chromosomes from the 12 homologous pairs. Crossing over during prophase I further mixes alleles between homologs, making each pollen grain genetically unique.": "",
  "A baby is born with Klinefelter syndrome (47, XXY). The father's chromosomes are normal (46, XY) and the mother's chromosomes are normal (46, XX). A genetic counselor determines that the extra X chromosome came from the mother. During which meiotic division in the mother did nondisjunction most likely occur?": "",
  "Mitotic nondisjunction after fertilization in the embryo, where one cell division produced an abnormal count": "",
  "The mother's meiosis I — the two X homologs failed to separate, producing an egg with XX; or meiosis II — the X sister chromatids failed to separate. Either could produce an XX egg that, when fertilized by a Y-bearing sperm, yields XXY": "",
  "The father's meiosis I, where he failed to separate the X and Y chromosomes into different daughter cells": "",
  "Crossing over during the father's meiosis created the extra X chromosome by duplicating part of the sex region": "",
  "Since the extra X came from the mother, the error was in maternal meiosis. In meiosis I, if the two X homologs failed to separate (both went to the same daughter cell), the resulting egg would have two X chromosomes (XX). In meiosis II, if the X sister chromatids failed to separate, the egg would also end up with XX. When this XX egg is fertilized by a normal Y-bearing sperm, the result is 47, XXY (Klinefelter syndrome). Genetic markers can sometimes distinguish meiosis I vs II errors.": "",
  "In a corn genetics experiment, a researcher crosses two pure-breeding parents that differ in two traits located on different chromosomes: kernel color (purple P dominant over yellow p) and kernel shape (smooth S dominant over wrinkled s). All F₁ offspring are PpSs. When the F₁ plants are crossed, the researcher expects a 9:3:3:1 phenotypic ratio in the F₂ generation. What meiotic process produces this characteristic ratio?": "",
  "Nondisjunction of the chromosomes carrying both genes": "",
  "Crossing over between the two gene loci during prophase I": "",
  "Linked inheritance — the genes travel together on the same chromosome": "",
  "Independent assortment — the Pp pair and Ss pair orient randomly and independently at metaphase I, so all four gamete types (PS, Ps, pS, ps) are produced in equal frequency": "",
  "The classic 9:3:3:1 dihybrid ratio depends on independent assortment. Because the P/p and S/s genes are on different chromosomes, each homologous pair orients independently at metaphase I. This produces four equally frequent gamete types: PS, Ps, pS, and ps. When these gametes combine randomly in the F₂ cross, the 16-square Punnett square yields the 9:3:3:1 ratio. If the genes were on the same chromosome (linked), they would deviate from this ratio unless crossing over separated them.": "",
  "A dog breeder notices that every puppy in a litter of 8 from the same two parents looks slightly different — different coat patterns, sizes, and temperaments. She asks why siblings from the same parents are not identical. Which combination of meiotic mechanisms BEST explains this variation?": "",
  "Mitosis during growth causes genetic differences between puppies by introducing random somatic mutations": "",
  "The puppies are identical genetically but the environment makes them look different through phenotypic plasticity": "",
  "Mutations during embryonic development cause all the differences between puppies in the same litter": "",
  "Crossing over (shuffles alleles between homologs), independent assortment (random chromosome combinations in each gamete), and random fertilization (each puppy comes from a different sperm-egg combination) together create unique offspring": "",
  "Sibling variation is produced by three mechanisms during sexual reproduction: (1) crossing over during prophase I creates recombinant chromosomes with new allele combinations, (2) independent assortment during metaphase I randomly distributes maternal and paternal chromosomes into gametes (2³⁹ ≈ 5.5 × 10¹¹ combinations in dogs with n = 39), and (3) random fertilization means each puppy develops from a different sperm-egg pair. With these mechanisms combined, the probability of two siblings being genetically identical (without being identical twins) is astronomically small.": "",
  "A geneticist studying an organism with 2n = 8 (4 pairs of chromosomes) wants to calculate the maximum number of genetically different gamete types produced by independent assortment alone (ignoring crossing over). How many different chromosome combinations are possible in each gamete?": "",
  "4 different combinations": "",
  "8 different combinations": "",
  "2⁸ = 256 different combinations": "",
  "2⁴ = 16 different chromosome combinations per gamete": "",
  "The formula for the number of possible gamete chromosome combinations from independent assortment is 2ⁿ, where n = the haploid number (number of homologous pairs). With 4 pairs (n = 4), there are 2⁴ = 16 possible combinations. Each pair independently orients at metaphase I, with the maternal or paternal homolog facing either pole. In humans (n = 23), this gives 2²³ ≈ 8.4 million. Note: this calculation ignores crossing over, which makes the actual number of unique gametes effectively infinite.": "",
  "During an IVF (in vitro fertilization) procedure, a doctor retrieves eggs from a patient. Alongside each mature egg, small non-functional cells called polar bodies are observed. Why does oogenesis produce these polar bodies instead of four equally-sized eggs like spermatogenesis produces four equal sperm?": "",
  "Polar bodies contain extra chromosomes that need to be discarded to maintain the correct haploid number": "",
  "The polar bodies will later mature into additional eggs if they are properly nourished in the ovarian follicle": "",
  "Asymmetric cytokinesis during oogenesis concentrates nearly all cytoplasm, organelles, mRNAs, and nutrients into one large egg — maximizing the resource stockpile for early embryonic development — while the polar bodies receive almost no cytoplasm and degenerate": "",
  "Oogenesis only undergoes one meiotic division instead of two, producing two equally sized daughter cells": "",
  "Oogenesis features extremely asymmetric cell division. During meiosis I and II, the cytoplasm divides unequally — one large cell receives ~95% of the cytoplasm while the polar body gets a tiny amount. This strategy evolved to concentrate all maternal resources (mRNAs, ribosomes, mitochondria, yolk proteins, nutrients) into a single large egg. The early embryo depends entirely on these stored maternal resources for its first divisions before its own genome activates. In IVF, polar body biopsy can be used for genetic testing without damaging the egg.": "",
  "Scientists compare meiosis in budding yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae, 2n = 32) with meiosis in humans (2n = 46). In yeast, meiosis produces four haploid spores enclosed in a structure called an ascus. Despite the vast evolutionary distance between yeast and humans, the core events of meiosis are remarkably conserved. Which shared feature is most fundamental?": "",
  "Both produce gametes that swim toward each other for fertilization using flagella-driven motility": "",
  "Both undergo homologous chromosome pairing, crossing over, and two sequential divisions that reduce the chromosome number from diploid to haploid — the core meiotic program is conserved across nearly all eukaryotes": "",
  "Both produce exactly four sperm cells from each meiosis, with identical chromosome arrangements": "",
  "Both use identical numbers of chromosomes during meiosis, reflecting a conserved ancestral genome size": "",
  "The fundamental meiotic program — homologous chromosome pairing (synapsis), crossing over (recombination), reductional division (meiosis I separating homologs), and equational division (meiosis II separating sister chromatids) — is conserved across virtually all sexually reproducing eukaryotes, from yeast to plants to animals. Key meiotic proteins (like Spo11 for initiating recombination and Rec8 cohesin) are homologous across species. This conservation over ~1 billion years of evolution underscores the importance of meiosis for genetic diversity and species survival.": "",
  "In honeybee colonies, females (queens and workers) develop from fertilized eggs and are diploid (2n = 32), while males (drones) develop from unfertilized eggs and are haploid (n = 16). When a haploid drone produces sperm, can he undergo normal meiosis? What special process occurs instead?": "",
  "Drones cannot undergo standard meiosis (no homologous pairs to separate) — instead, they produce sperm through a modified process where the first division is abortive and the second is essentially mitotic, producing haploid sperm genetically identical to the drone's cells": "",
  "Drones do not produce sperm because they are haploid and lack the cellular machinery for gametogenesis": "",
  "Drones double their chromosomes to become diploid before undergoing standard meiosis and gamete production": "",
  "Drones undergo normal meiosis like diploid organisms, simply starting with half the usual chromosome number": "",
  "Honeybee drones are haploid (n = 16) and lack homologous chromosome pairs. Standard meiosis I (which separates homologs) cannot occur normally. Instead, drone spermatogenesis involves a modified division: the cell undergoes a pseudo-meiosis where one division is essentially skipped or abortive, and the functional division separates sister chromatids (similar to meiosis II/mitosis). The resulting sperm are haploid (n = 16) and genetically identical to the drone's own cells. This haplodiploidy system means all sperm from one drone are genetically identical.": "",
  "Seedless watermelons are produced by creating triploid plants (3n = 33). Breeders first treat a normal diploid watermelon (2n = 22) with colchicine to produce a tetraploid (4n = 44), then cross the tetraploid with a normal diploid. Why are the resulting triploid plants unable to produce seeds?": "",
  "Triploid plants have too many chromosomes to survive, so they cannot develop into mature fruiting plants": "",
  "Colchicine makes the plants permanently sterile by destroying their DNA through chemical mutagenesis": "",
  "With three sets of chromosomes (3n = 33), homologous chromosomes cannot pair properly during meiosis I — trivalents form instead of bivalents, leading to uneven chromosome segregation and non-viable gametes, so no seeds develop": "",
  "Triploid plants cannot undergo mitosis, so they never grow flowers or produce any reproductive structures": "",
  "Triploid organisms (3n) have three copies of each chromosome rather than the normal two. During meiosis I, chromosomes pair as homologs — but with three copies, they form trivalents (groups of three) instead of normal bivalents (pairs). Trivalents cannot segregate evenly into two groups, so the resulting gametes get unbalanced chromosome numbers (some chromosomes have 2 copies, others have 1). These aneuploid gametes are almost always non-viable. Since seeds require successful fertilization, the triploid watermelon is effectively seedless.": "",
  "Researchers studying the nematode C. elegans notice that crossing over events are not evenly distributed across chromosomes — some regions have many crossovers ('hotspots') while others have very few ('coldspots'). They also observe that each chromosome arm receives exactly one crossover per meiosis (crossover interference). Why is at least one crossover per chromosome pair essential for proper meiosis?": "",
  "Crossovers are needed to condense chromosomes during prophase by providing physical tension along the arms": "",
  "Crossovers provide the energy needed for chromosome movement by generating ATP at the exchange sites": "",
  "At least one crossover per homologous pair creates a physical chiasma connection that holds the homologs together until anaphase I — without this connection, homologs may segregate randomly, causing nondisjunction and aneuploidy": "",
  "Crossovers are needed to replicate DNA during S phase by creating replication origins at exchange points": "",
  "The obligate crossover (at least one per chromosome pair) serves a critical mechanical function beyond generating genetic diversity. The chiasma formed by crossing over, together with sister chromatid cohesion distal to the chiasma, physically links the two homologs. This connection ensures that homologous chromosomes orient correctly at the metaphase I plate with tension from opposing spindle poles. Without a chiasma, homologs have no physical link after the synaptonemal complex dissolves, leading to random segregation (nondisjunction). C. elegans enforces exactly one crossover per chromosome through crossover interference — a mechanism that ensures proper meiotic segregation.": ""
}